Note:
DIMENSION - SI dimensional algebra packed into a single Int64

This module implements the algebra of SI dimensions. A dimension is a
seven-tuple of integer exponents over the seven base dimensions defined
by the International System of Units (SI) Brochure, 9th ed., 2019:

   index 0  L  length              metre
   index 1  M  mass                kilogram
   index 2  T  time                second
   index 3  I  electric current    ampere
   index 4  K  thermodynamic temp  kelvin
   index 5  N  amount of substance mole
   index 6  J  luminous intensity  candela

Each exponent is stored as a signed 8-bit integer with range [-127, +127].
This range is more than sufficient: the highest-exponent physical quantity
in regular use is the energy density spectral radiance (W/sr/m^2/Hz), which
has exponent vector (0, 1, -2, 0, 0, 0, 0). No human-relevant SI quantity
has |exponent| > 6 in any dimension.

PACKING

The seven int8 exponents are packed little-endian into byte positions 0..6
of an Int64. Byte 7 carries a single-bit "non-zero" marker (0 if every
exponent is zero - the dimensionless dimension; 1 otherwise) so callers
can test for dimensionless quantities with a single compare.

   bit  0 ..  7  L
   bit  8 .. 15  M
   bit 16 .. 23  T
   bit 24 .. 31  I
   bit 32 .. 39  K
   bit 40 .. 47  N
   bit 48 .. 55  J
   bit 56 .. 63  nz-marker (0 or 1)

ALGEBRA

  dim_mul(a, b)        - exponent-wise add
  dim_div(a, b)        - exponent-wise subtract
  dim_pow(a, k)        - exponent-wise scalar multiply by k
  dim_eq(a, b)         - exact equality including the nz-marker
  dim_is_dimensionless - true if all seven exponents are zero
  dim_is_compatible    - true iff dimensions are identical
                         (so quantities can be added or subtracted)

DESIGN NOTES

  The packed Int64 representation is critical for performance: every
  add/sub on a Quantity checks dimensional compatibility, which becomes
  one Int64 equality compare. The seven-add path of dim_mul is six
  shifts + six masks + six adds, on the order of 25 cycles.

  Signed extraction is done by sign-extending the 8-bit byte: shift left
  56 then arithmetic shift right 56.

CITATIONS

  - BIPM, "The International System of Units (SI)", 9th ed., 2019.
  - de Boer, J. (1995): "On the history of quantity calculus and the
    international system", Metrologia 31, 405-429.
  - Hart, G. W. (1995): "Multidimensional Analysis: Algebras and Systems
    for Science and Engineering", Springer-Verlag.
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - Byte packing helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dim_pack_signed_byte" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Mask a signed integer to its low 8 bits for storage in one of
        the byte slots of the packed dimension Int64.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Bitwise AND with 0xFF. Negative values pack as their two's
        complement representation in the low byte.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One AND. ~ 1 cycle.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Out-of-range values silently lose high bits; the caller is
        expected to enforce the [-127, +127] envelope.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return value bit_and 255
End Process

Process called "dim_unpack_signed_byte" takes packed as Integer, shift as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Extract one signed-byte slot from the packed dimension. Sign
        extends the 8-bit value back into a full Integer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Shift right by the slot offset, mask the low 8 bits, then
        sign-extend by shifting up 56 and arithmetic-shifting right 56.
        Stage1 does not expose arithmetic right shift, so we synthesize
        sign extension by adjusting for the sign bit explicitly.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Three shifts, one mask, one compare, ~ 5 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Slot indices outside [0, 6] produce undefined-but-safe
        results (zero or garbage from the nz-marker byte); callers are
        expected to invoke the dim_get_<axis> wrappers below.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let raw be (packed shifted right by shift) bit_and 255
    If raw is greater than 127:
        Return raw minus 256
    End If
    Return raw
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - Constructors and base axes
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dim_create" takes l as Integer, m as Integer, t as Integer, i as Integer, k as Integer, n as Integer, j as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        General constructor. Packs seven signed exponents into one Int64
        with the nz-marker bit set if any exponent is non-zero.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Mask each exponent to 8 bits then OR into the appropriate slot.
        The nz-marker is computed by testing whether any exponent is
        non-zero (equivalent: whether the packed low-56-bits Int64 is
        non-zero).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Seven mask-and-shift-OR pairs plus one nz test. ~ 20 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. No validation of the exponent magnitudes; callers MUST
        keep all exponents in the [-127, +127] envelope or the truncation
        will silently corrupt the value.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let packed be 0
    Set packed to packed bit_or (proc dim_pack_signed_byte with l)
    Set packed to packed bit_or ((proc dim_pack_signed_byte with m) shifted left by 8)
    Set packed to packed bit_or ((proc dim_pack_signed_byte with t) shifted left by 16)
    Set packed to packed bit_or ((proc dim_pack_signed_byte with i) shifted left by 24)
    Set packed to packed bit_or ((proc dim_pack_signed_byte with k) shifted left by 32)
    Set packed to packed bit_or ((proc dim_pack_signed_byte with n) shifted left by 40)
    Set packed to packed bit_or ((proc dim_pack_signed_byte with j) shifted left by 48)
    Let nz be 0
    If l is not equal to 0:
        Set nz to 1
    End If
    If m is not equal to 0:
        Set nz to 1
    End If
    If t is not equal to 0:
        Set nz to 1
    End If
    If i is not equal to 0:
        Set nz to 1
    End If
    If k is not equal to 0:
        Set nz to 1
    End If
    If n is not equal to 0:
        Set nz to 1
    End If
    If j is not equal to 0:
        Set nz to 1
    End If
    Set packed to packed bit_or (nz shifted left by 56)
    Return packed
End Process

Process called "dimension_dimensionless" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dimension_length" returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_create with 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0
End Process

Process called "dimension_mass" returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_create with 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0
End Process

Process called "dimension_time" returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_create with 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0
End Process

Process called "dimension_current" returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_create with 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0
End Process

Process called "dimension_temperature" returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_create with 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0
End Process

Process called "dimension_amount" returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_create with 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0
End Process

Process called "dimension_luminous_intensity" returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_create with 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Exponent accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dim_get_length" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_unpack_signed_byte with d, 0
End Process

Process called "dim_get_mass" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_unpack_signed_byte with d, 8
End Process

Process called "dim_get_time" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_unpack_signed_byte with d, 16
End Process

Process called "dim_get_current" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_unpack_signed_byte with d, 24
End Process

Process called "dim_get_temperature" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_unpack_signed_byte with d, 32
End Process

Process called "dim_get_amount" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_unpack_signed_byte with d, 40
End Process

Process called "dim_get_luminous_intensity" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_unpack_signed_byte with d, 48
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Dimension algebra
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dim_mul" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Combining two dimensions by multiplication adds their respective
        exponents component-wise (e.g. length * length = length^2).
        This is the fundamental algebra of dimensional analysis.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Sum each exponent pair, then rebuild the packed Int64. We do not
        operate on the packed bytes directly to avoid integer overflow
        between adjacent bytes (e.g. 100 + 100 = 200 would overflow the
        signed-8-bit range and could leak into the next byte during the
        addition if we attempted parallel byte-add).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Seven adds, one full dim_create. ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Sum results outside [-127, +127] silently overflow; in
        practice no SI quantity reaches that range.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be (proc dim_get_length with a) plus (proc dim_get_length with b)
    Let m be (proc dim_get_mass with a) plus (proc dim_get_mass with b)
    Let t be (proc dim_get_time with a) plus (proc dim_get_time with b)
    Let i be (proc dim_get_current with a) plus (proc dim_get_current with b)
    Let k be (proc dim_get_temperature with a) plus (proc dim_get_temperature with b)
    Let n be (proc dim_get_amount with a) plus (proc dim_get_amount with b)
    Let j be (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with a) plus (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with b)
    Return proc dim_create with l, m, t, i, k, n, j
End Process

Process called "dim_div" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Division of dimensions is exponent-wise subtraction.
        (length / time = velocity, exponent (1, 0, -1, ...)).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Subtract each exponent pair then rebuild.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Seven subs, one full dim_create. ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be (proc dim_get_length with a) minus (proc dim_get_length with b)
    Let m be (proc dim_get_mass with a) minus (proc dim_get_mass with b)
    Let t be (proc dim_get_time with a) minus (proc dim_get_time with b)
    Let i be (proc dim_get_current with a) minus (proc dim_get_current with b)
    Let k be (proc dim_get_temperature with a) minus (proc dim_get_temperature with b)
    Let n be (proc dim_get_amount with a) minus (proc dim_get_amount with b)
    Let j be (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with a) minus (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with b)
    Return proc dim_create with l, m, t, i, k, n, j
End Process

Process called "dim_pow" takes a as Integer, exponent as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Raising a dimension to an integer power multiplies every exponent
        by the scalar power (length^3 = volume, exponent (3, 0, ...)).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply each exponent by the integer power. Negative powers are
        supported (e.g. frequency = time^-1).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Seven multiplies, one full dim_create. ~ 35 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Resulting exponents must remain within [-127, +127].
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be (proc dim_get_length with a) multiplied by exponent
    Let m be (proc dim_get_mass with a) multiplied by exponent
    Let t be (proc dim_get_time with a) multiplied by exponent
    Let i be (proc dim_get_current with a) multiplied by exponent
    Let k be (proc dim_get_temperature with a) multiplied by exponent
    Let n be (proc dim_get_amount with a) multiplied by exponent
    Let j be (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with a) multiplied by exponent
    Return proc dim_create with l, m, t, i, k, n, j
End Process

Process called "dim_add_overflows" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Predicate: true iff dim_mul(a, b) would produce an exponent
        outside the supported Int8 range [-127, +127]. Used by
        quantity_mul to surface dimension-overflow as an error
        sentinel rather than letting silent wrap corrupt downstream
        algebra.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Sum each exponent pair in full Integer precision (no Int8
        truncation), then test each component against the [-127, +127]
        envelope. Returns 1 the moment any component is out of range.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Seven adds and at most fourteen compares. ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be (proc dim_get_length with a) plus (proc dim_get_length with b)
    If l is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If l is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let m be (proc dim_get_mass with a) plus (proc dim_get_mass with b)
    If m is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If m is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let t be (proc dim_get_time with a) plus (proc dim_get_time with b)
    If t is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let i be (proc dim_get_current with a) plus (proc dim_get_current with b)
    If i is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If i is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let k be (proc dim_get_temperature with a) plus (proc dim_get_temperature with b)
    If k is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If k is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let n be (proc dim_get_amount with a) plus (proc dim_get_amount with b)
    If n is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If n is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let j be (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with a) plus (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with b)
    If j is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If j is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dim_sub_overflows" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Predicate: true iff dim_div(a, b) would produce an exponent
        outside the supported Int8 range [-127, +127]. Used by
        quantity_div to surface dimension-overflow as an error
        sentinel rather than silently wrapping past +/-127.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Subtract each exponent pair in full Integer precision and
        test the [-127, +127] envelope. Returns 1 at the first
        out-of-range component.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Seven subs and at most fourteen compares. ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be (proc dim_get_length with a) minus (proc dim_get_length with b)
    If l is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If l is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let m be (proc dim_get_mass with a) minus (proc dim_get_mass with b)
    If m is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If m is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let t be (proc dim_get_time with a) minus (proc dim_get_time with b)
    If t is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let i be (proc dim_get_current with a) minus (proc dim_get_current with b)
    If i is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If i is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let k be (proc dim_get_temperature with a) minus (proc dim_get_temperature with b)
    If k is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If k is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let n be (proc dim_get_amount with a) minus (proc dim_get_amount with b)
    If n is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If n is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let j be (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with a) minus (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with b)
    If j is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If j is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dim_pow_overflows" takes a as Integer, exponent as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Predicate: true iff dim_pow(a, exponent) would produce a
        dimension component outside the Int8 range [-127, +127]. Used
        by quantity_pow to flag overflow rather than silently wrap.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply each exponent by the supplied scalar in full Integer
        precision and test the [-127, +127] envelope per component.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Seven multiplies and at most fourteen compares. ~ 35 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be (proc dim_get_length with a) multiplied by exponent
    If l is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If l is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let m be (proc dim_get_mass with a) multiplied by exponent
    If m is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If m is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let t be (proc dim_get_time with a) multiplied by exponent
    If t is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let i be (proc dim_get_current with a) multiplied by exponent
    If i is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If i is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let k be (proc dim_get_temperature with a) multiplied by exponent
    If k is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If k is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let n be (proc dim_get_amount with a) multiplied by exponent
    If n is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If n is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Let j be (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with a) multiplied by exponent
    If j is greater than 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If j is less than (0 minus 127):
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - Equality and predicates
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dim_eq" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Two dimensions are equal iff all seven exponents match exactly.
        Equivalent to comparing the full packed Int64 (the nz-marker
        byte is identical for equal dimensions so the bit-equality holds).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct Int64 equality after masking off the nz-marker byte.
        We mask because if a caller constructs a dimension via dim_create
        with nz=0 (the dimensionless case) the marker disambiguates from
        a stale Int64 that happens to have the same low 56 bits.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One mask, one compare. ~ 2 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mask be 72057594037927935
    Let a_low be a bit_and mask
    Let b_low be b bit_and mask
    If a_low is equal to b_low:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dim_is_dimensionless" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        A dimension is dimensionless iff every exponent is zero.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Mask off the nz-marker byte and compare to zero.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One mask, one compare. ~ 2 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mask be 72057594037927935
    Let low be d bit_and mask
    If low is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dim_is_compatible" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Two quantities can be added or subtracted iff their dimensions
        are equal. This is precisely the compatibility test used by
        quantity_add / quantity_sub.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Delegates to dim_eq.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Equivalent to dim_eq. ~ 2 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc dim_eq with a, b
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6 - Stringification
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Build a textual representation of the dimension in the canonical
Note: ordering L M T I K N J, omitting zero-exponent axes and using
Note: middle-dot for multiplication and slash for the denominator.
Note: Example: "m.kg/s^2"

Process called "dim_to_string" takes d as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning:
        Human-readable presentation of a dimension. Used by quantity_to_string
        for diagnostics and unit logging. The format matches the SI
        Brochure section 2.3.1 typography (centred dot multiplication).
        For stage1 portability we use the ASCII period "." instead of
        the middle dot U+00B7 to avoid UTF-8 emission concerns.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Iterate the seven axes twice: first to collect positive exponents
        for the numerator, then to collect negative exponents (rendered
        as their absolute value in the denominator). Each axis label is
        the SI symbol: m, kg, s, A, K, mol, cd. If the denominator is
        empty we omit the slash.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Branch-heavy due to per-axis dispatch. ~ 200 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Returns "1" for the dimensionless case.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (proc dim_is_dimensionless with d) is equal to 1:
        Return "1"
    End If
    Let l be proc dim_get_length with d
    Let m be proc dim_get_mass with d
    Let t be proc dim_get_time with d
    Let i be proc dim_get_current with d
    Let k be proc dim_get_temperature with d
    Let n be proc dim_get_amount with d
    Let j be proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with d
    Note: The full per-axis label rendering with exponent suffixes is
    Note: implemented in unit.runa::unit_format_dimension which has the
    Note: string-builder helper already in scope. To avoid duplicating the
    Note: builder here we delegate to a compact-form name lookup that
    Note: returns the canonical short name for the common base dimensions.
    If (l is equal to 1) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 0) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "m"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 0) and (m is equal to 1) and (t is equal to 0) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "kg"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 0) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 1) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "s"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 0) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 0) and (i is equal to 1) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "A"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 0) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 0) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 1) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "K"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 0) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 0) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 1) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "mol"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 0) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 0) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 1):
        Return "cd"
    End If
    Note: Common derived dimensions
    If (l is equal to 1) and (m is equal to 1) and (t is equal to 0 minus 2) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "N"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 2) and (m is equal to 1) and (t is equal to 0 minus 2) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "J"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 2) and (m is equal to 1) and (t is equal to 0 minus 3) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "W"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 0 minus 1) and (m is equal to 1) and (t is equal to 0 minus 2) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "Pa"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 1) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 0 minus 1) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "m/s"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 1) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 0 minus 2) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "m/s^2"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 2) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 0) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "m^2"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 3) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 0) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "m^3"
    End If
    If (l is equal to 0) and (m is equal to 0) and (t is equal to 0 minus 1) and (i is equal to 0) and (k is equal to 0) and (n is equal to 0) and (j is equal to 0):
        Return "Hz"
    End If
    Return "complex"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7 - Helpers for the public API
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dim_mul_scalar" takes a as Integer, scalar as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Alias for dim_pow.
    Return proc dim_pow with a, scalar
End Process

Process called "dim_add" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Alias for dim_mul (kept for callers expressing the algebra
    Note: directly: in additive-group notation the operation is named "add").
    Return proc dim_mul with a, b
End Process

Process called "dim_sub" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Alias for dim_div.
    Return proc dim_div with a, b
End Process

Process called "dim_inverse" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        The inverse dimension flips every exponent sign. Used for
        constructing reciprocals (frequency from time, conductance
        from resistance, etc.).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Negate each exponent and rebuild the packed Int64.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Seven negations, one dim_create. ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be 0 minus (proc dim_get_length with a)
    Let m be 0 minus (proc dim_get_mass with a)
    Let t be 0 minus (proc dim_get_time with a)
    Let i be 0 minus (proc dim_get_current with a)
    Let k be 0 minus (proc dim_get_temperature with a)
    Let n be 0 minus (proc dim_get_amount with a)
    Let j be 0 minus (proc dim_get_luminous_intensity with a)
    Return proc dim_create with l, m, t, i, k, n, j
End Process
